    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-07-27T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-07-27T13:00:00-05:00" n="181"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d181">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">690D. 91/7–2751: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gifford</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-07-27T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 27, 1951—7 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>565. <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 500 July 25 to Dept rptd New Delhi
                    15 Karachi 16 <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss> 4. <gloss target="#t_CRO1"
                        >CRO</gloss> was just about to instruct New Delhi and Karachi make
                    representations to <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> and <gloss
                        target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss> along lines similar to those of US when report
                    received of Liaquat’s invitation to Nehru. Instructions have now been withdrawn
                    for restudy.</p>
                <pb facs="0332" n="1796" xml:id="pg_1796"/>
                <p>President <gloss target="#t_CRO1">CRO</gloss> thinking in view of rebuff to
                    Menzies, apparently polite but unresponsive reaction to US move, and probable
                    refusal by Nehru of Liaquat’s invitation, is to suggest to both leaders that a
                    meeting be arranged, perhaps on neutral ground and without conditions of any
                    kind. If Attlee approves, such a line may now be adopted.</p>
                <p>Rptd priority info New Delhi 17, Karachi 17 <gloss target="#t_USUN1"
                    >USUN</gloss>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gifford</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
